eads/jdanjou.png" width="100" height="84" alt="" align="right" />  <p class="first">Since I have started to use <a href="http://www.orgmode.org">Org-mode</a>, I though it was missing something to\nhave appointment locations on a map. Of course, it\'s easy to get a <em>LOCATION</em>\nproperty from an entry, and then <em>browse-url</em> on <a href="http://maps.google.com">Google Maps</a>.</p>\n\n<p>But it is <strong>too</strong> easy for me, so once again I said:</p>\n\n<p>Challenge accepted!</p>\n\n<p>I will bring Google Maps into Emacs.</p>\n\n<p>After a few hours of works, the <a href="http://julien.danjou.info/google-maps-el.html">google-maps-el project</a> works!</p>\n\n<center>\n<p><img src="http://julien.danjou.info/images/emacs-google-maps.png" alt="" /></p>\n</center>\n\n<p>It fully implements the <a href="http://code.google.com/apis/maps/documentation/staticmaps/">Google Static Maps API</a> and the\n<a href="http://code.google.com/apis/maps/documentation/geocoding/">Google Maps Geocoding API</a>.</p>\n\n<p>You can type <strong>M-x google-maps</strong> and type some place to see it marked on map. Of\ncourse you can do much more, as seen in the screen shot above.</p>\n\n<p>I\'ve also completed all of this with a small <a href="http://git.naquadah.org/?p=~jd/jd-el.git;a=blob;f=org-location-google-maps.el;hb=HEAD">org-location-google-maps</a> which\nsimply show a Google Maps\' map for the location of an event in <em>Org mode</em> by\npressing C-c M-l in an Org buffer or in the Org agenda.</p>', 'guidislink': True, 'title_detail': {'base': 'http://planet.debian.org/rss20.xml', 'type': 'text/plain', 'value': u'Julien Danjou: M-x google-maps', 'language': None}, 'link': u'http://julien.danjou.info/blog/index.html#M%2Dx%20google%2Dmaps', 'id': u'http://julien.danjou.info/blog/index.html#M%2Dx%20google%2Dmaps'}

Entry title: Julien Danjou: M-x google-maps
Entry link: http://julien.danjou.info/blog/index.html#M%2Dx%20google%2Dmaps
Entry description: <img src="http://planet.debian.org/heads/jdanjou.png" width="100" height="84" alt="" align="right" />  <p class="first">Since I have started to use <a href="http://www.orgmode.org">Org-mode</a>, I though it was missing something to
have appointment locations on a map. Of course, it's easy to get a <em>LOCATION</em>
property from an entry, and then <em>browse-url</em> on <a href="http://maps.google.com">Google Maps</a>.</p>

<p>But it is <strong>too</strong> easy for me, so once again I said:</p>

<p>Challenge accepted!</p>

<p>I will bring Google Maps into Emacs.</p>

<p>After a few hours of works, the <a href="http://julien.danjou.info/google-maps-el.html">google-maps-el project</a> works!</p>

<center>
<p><img src="http://julien.danjou.info/images/emacs-google-maps.png" alt="" /></p>
</center>

<p>It fully implements the <a href="http://code.google.com/apis/maps/documentation/staticmaps/">Google Static Maps API</a> and the
<a href="http://code.google.com/apis/maps/documentation/geocoding/">Google Maps Geocoding API</a>.</p>

<p>You can type <strong>M-x google-maps</strong> and type some place to see it marked on map. Of
course you can do much more, as seen in the screen shot above.</p>

<p>I've also completed all of this with a small <a href="http://git.naquadah.org/?p=~jd/jd-el.git;a=blob;f=org-location-google-maps.el;hb=HEAD">org-location-google-maps</a> which
simply show a Google Maps' map for the location of an event in <em>Org mode</em> by
pressing C-c M-l in an Org buffer or in the Org agenda.</p>
Entry date: Mon, 28 Jun 2010 00:00:00 +0000
Entry date_parsed: (2010, 6, 28, 0, 0, 0, 0, 179, 0)
Entry id: http://julien.danjou.info/blog/index.html#M%2Dx%20google%2Dmaps

