{'summary_detail': {'base': 'http://planet.debian.org/rss20.xml', 'type': 'text/html', 'value': u'<img src="http://planet.debian.org/heads/myon.png" width="71" height="95" alt="" align="right" />  <p>Since coreutils 8.1 (in Squeeze, not Lenny), there is a command that simply\nprints out how many processors (cores, processing units) are available:</p>\n\n<pre><code>$ nproc\n2\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>The use case is obvious:</p>\n\n<pre><code>$ make -j $(nproc)\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>On a side note, this is gnulib\'s nproc module wrapped into a C program. If you\ndidn\'t know gnulib before (it had slipped my attention until recently), it is a\nlibrary of portability functions and other useful things. Adding it to a\nproject is simply done by calling gnulib-tool and tweaking a few lines in the\nautomake/whatever build scripts.</p>\n\n<p><i>PS: do not use nproc unconditionally in debian/rules. Parse\nDEB_BUILD_OPTIONS for "parallel" instead.</i></p>', 'language': None}, 'updated_parsed': (2010, 6, 23, 7, 58, 49, 2, 174, 0), 'links': [{'href': u'http://www.df7cb.de/blog/2010/nproc.html', 'type': 'text/html', 'rel': 'alternate'}], 'title': u'Christoph Berg: Cool Unix Features: nproc', 'updated': u'Wed, 23 Jun 2010 07:58:49 +0000', 'summary': u'<img src="http://planet.debian.org/heads/myon.png" width="71" height="95" alt="" align="right" />  <p>Since coreutils 8.1 (in Squeeze, not Lenny), there is a command that simply\nprints out how many processors (cores, processing units) are available:</p>\n\n<pre><code>$ nproc\n2\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>The use case is obvious:</p>\n\n<pre><code>$ make -j $(nproc)\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>On a side note, this is gnulib\'s nproc module wrapped into a C program. If you\ndidn\'t know gnulib before (it had slipped my attention until recently), it is a\nlibrary of portability functions and other useful things. Adding it to a\nproject is simply done by calling gnulib-tool and tweaking a few lines in the\nautomake/whatever build scripts.</p>\n\n<p><i>PS: do not use nproc unconditionally in debian/rules. Parse\nDEB_BUILD_OPTIONS for "parallel" instead.</i></p>', 'guidislink': True, 'title_detail': {'base': 'http://planet.debian.org/rss20.xml', 'type': 'text/plain', 'value': u'Christoph Berg: Cool Unix Features: nproc', 'language': None}, 'link': u'http://www.df7cb.de/blog/2010/nproc.html', 'id': u'http://www.df7cb.de/blog/2010/nproc.html'}

Entry title: Christoph Berg: Cool Unix Features: nproc
Entry link: http://www.df7cb.de/blog/2010/nproc.html
Entry description: <img src="http://planet.debian.org/heads/myon.png" width="71" height="95" alt="" align="right" />  <p>Since coreutils 8.1 (in Squeeze, not Lenny), there is a command that simply
prints out how many processors (cores, processing units) are available:</p>

<pre><code>$ nproc
2
</code></pre>

<p>The use case is obvious:</p>

<pre><code>$ make -j $(nproc)
</code></pre>

<p>On a side note, this is gnulib's nproc module wrapped into a C program. If you
didn't know gnulib before (it had slipped my attention until recently), it is a
library of portability functions and other useful things. Adding it to a
project is simply done by calling gnulib-tool and tweaking a few lines in the
automake/whatever build scripts.</p>

<p><i>PS: do not use nproc unconditionally in debian/rules. Parse
DEB_BUILD_OPTIONS for "parallel" instead.</i></p>
