{'summary_detail': {'base': 'http://planet.debian.org/rss20.xml', 'type': 'text/html', 'value': u'<img src="http://planet.debian.org/heads/joeyh2.png" width="84" height="75" alt="" align="right" />  <p>Here on the porch at Dani\'s, enjoying the chill breeze as a distant\nstorm passes by, and the last half hour of daylight, it seems right\nto have been awake to see the solstice dawn, and out in the world all\nday. Though after 16 hours, the part of the day spent napping in a\nhammock barely seems enough.</p>\n\n<p>Such an early start to this day, first visiting a small-town garage with\nDad, where skype video calls were being made, and then racing the morning\nheat north, out of South Carolina.</p>\n\n<p>(I can\'t hear "frakking water" on the radio without snickering.\nCongratulations to all the news-people who pulled that phrase off\ntoday.)</p>\n\n<p>A long drive punctuated by picking up my passenger, and my own \n<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goodbye_solo">Goodbye Solo</a> drive up by Blowing Rock,\nlooking in the mirror at passenger dreaming in the backseat. Thinking about\nhow, in the flat lands, cresting a long, slow hill, I often feel as if the road\nahead could at any moment vanish, sending the car plunging into nothing; a\nlatent agoraphobia. And in the mountains, as the road narrows and winds, I\'m\nalways confident it continues solidly around each blind bend.</p>', 'language': None}, 'updated_parsed': (2010, 6, 22, 15, 53, 7, 1, 173, 0), 'links': [{'href': u'http://kitenet.net/~joey/blog/entry/longest_day/', 'type': 'text/html', 'rel': 'alternate'}], 'title': u'Joey Hess: longest day', 'updated': u'Tue, 22 Jun 2010 15:53:07 +0000', 'summary': u'<img src="http://planet.debian.org/heads/joeyh2.png" width="84" height="75" alt="" align="right" />  <p>Here on the porch at Dani\'s, enjoying the chill breeze as a distant\nstorm passes by, and the last half hour of daylight, it seems right\nto have been awake to see the solstice dawn, and out in the world all\nday. Though after 16 hours, the part of the day spent napping in a\nhammock barely seems enough.</p>\n\n<p>Such an early start to this day, first visiting a small-town garage with\nDad, where skype video calls were being made, and then racing the morning\nheat north, out of South Carolina.</p>\n\n<p>(I can\'t hear "frakking water" on the radio without snickering.\nCongratulations to all the news-people who pulled that phrase off\ntoday.)</p>\n\n<p>A long drive punctuated by picking up my passenger, and my own \n<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goodbye_solo">Goodbye Solo</a> drive up by Blowing Rock,\nlooking in the mirror at passenger dreaming in the backseat. Thinking about\nhow, in the flat lands, cresting a long, slow hill, I often feel as if the road\nahead could at any moment vanish, sending the car plunging into nothing; a\nlatent agoraphobia. And in the mountains, as the road narrows and winds, I\'m\nalways confident it continues solidly around each blind bend.</p>', 'guidislink': True, 'title_detail': {'base': 'http://planet.debian.org/rss20.xml', 'type': 'text/plain', 'value': u'Joey Hess: longest day', 'language': None}, 'link': u'http://kitenet.net/~joey/blog/entry/longest_day/', 'id': u'http://kitenet.net/~joey/blog/entry/longest_day/'}

Entry title: Joey Hess: longest day
Entry link: http://kitenet.net/~joey/blog/entry/longest_day/
Entry description: <img src="http://planet.debian.org/heads/joeyh2.png" width="84" height="75" alt="" align="right" />  <p>Here on the porch at Dani's, enjoying the chill breeze as a distant
storm passes by, and the last half hour of daylight, it seems right
to have been awake to see the solstice dawn, and out in the world all
day. Though after 16 hours, the part of the day spent napping in a
hammock barely seems enough.</p>

<p>Such an early start to this day, first visiting a small-town garage with
Dad, where skype video calls were being made, and then racing the morning
heat north, out of South Carolina.</p>

<p>(I can't hear "frakking water" on the radio without snickering.
Congratulations to all the news-people who pulled that phrase off
today.)</p>

<p>A long drive punctuated by picking up my passenger, and my own 
<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goodbye_solo">Goodbye Solo</a> drive up by Blowing Rock,
looking in the mirror at passenger dreaming in the backseat. Thinking about
how, in the flat lands, cresting a long, slow hill, I often feel as if the road
ahead could at any moment vanish, sending the car plunging into nothing; a
latent agoraphobia. And in the mountains, as the road narrows and winds, I'm
always confident it continues solidly around each blind bend.</p>
Entry date: Tue, 22 Jun 2010 15:53:07 +0000
